   "source": [
    "## 8b. How does the model actually score a team?\n",
    "\n",
    "Now we have a trained model on disk, but a fair question is: when we hand it a\n",
    "team, what is it actually *doing* to come up with that 0-to-1 number?\n",
    "\n",
    "The model is not one mysterious thing. It is a stack of about 200 small\n",
    "decision trees. When a team comes in:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Every tree asks 3 to 5 yes/no questions** about the team's features\n",
    "   (things like \"is `teammate_logweight_mean` greater than 1.5?\", or\n",
    "   \"is `type_unique_count` greater than 5?\").\n",
    "2. Based on the answers, each tree **votes a small adjustment**: a number\n",
    "   like +0.20, -0.10, +0.05.\n",
    "3. **All 200 adjustments are summed.** That gives one raw number, which can\n",
    "   be any positive or negative value.\n",
    "4. The raw number is **squished into 0-1 by the sigmoid function**. That is\n",
    "   the viability score the UI shows.\n",
    "\n",
    "So a team's score is not \"one big decision.\" It is the cumulative result of\n",
    "200 tiny tugs, each from one tree, each tugging the running total a little\n",
    "up or a little down.\n",
    "\n",
    "The diagram below illustrates the idea. The numbers are made up; the next\n",
    "cell after the diagram shows the same process running on a real team using\n",
    "the real trained model.\n"
   ]
  },
